{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502421"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1858"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1858"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.28,0.63,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1858"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27030"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man is five days post-hospitalisation for an episode of acute diverticulitis which was complicated by a 2cm pericolic abscess (as demonstrated on abdominal CT imaging performed with IV contrast). He has responded well to intravenous antibiotics and is about to be discharged home, with the plan to perform a colonoscopy in approximately six week\u0027s time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important reason to perform a colonoscopy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["To confirm the diagnosis","To assess the extent of the diverticular disease","To exclude underlying malignancy","To biopsy the site of inflammation","To dilate any strictures of the sigmoid colon"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients who have had an episode of acute complicated diverticulitis should have a colonoscopy at approximately six weeks following their episode. The purpose of this is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eexclude underlying malignancy, \u003C/strong\u003Especifically colorectal cancer (CRC), as these patients have been found to have a higher incidence of CRC than the general population. Our patient has complicated diverticulitis (Hinchey classification Ib due to the pericolic abscess), and therefore requires direct visualisation to exclude malignancy. Ambiguity lies with patients who have acute uncomplicated diverticulitis, where this should be performed if over the age of 70 or no colonoscopy within the preceding two to three years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent CT imaging can diagnose diverticulitis and its complications with a sensitivity of 94% and specificity of 99%, therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy is not usually required to confirm the diagnosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Colonoscopy is delayed by six weeks for inflammation to settle down and thus minimise the risk of free perforation from gas insufflation and bowel manipulation, given the underlying pathomechanism of diverticulitis is micro- or macro-perforation. Therefore the purpose is not to\u003Cstrong\u003E biopsy the site of inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E, but to look for an underlying mucosal lesion. While a colonoscopy can determine the \u003Cstrong\u003Eextent of diverticular disease\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edilate diverticular strictures\u003C/strong\u003E, neither of these are the purpose of this procedure in the clinical context of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Colonoscopy should be performed four to six weeks after an episode of acute complicated diverticulitis to exclude underlying colorectal cancer."],"references":["Young-Fadok TM. Diverticulitis. N Eng J Med 2018;379:1635-42. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMcp1800468?url_ver=Z39.88-2003\u0026rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org\u0026rfr_dat=cr_pub%20%200pubmed","Diaz JJT, Asenjo BDA, Soriano MR, Fernandez CJ, Aurusa JOS, Renteria JPBH. Efficacy of colonoscopy after an episode of acute diverticulitis and risk of colorectal cancer. Ann Gastroenterol 2020;33(1):68-72. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6928487/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27030"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27030"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-29T21:11:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-29T21:11:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1858"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42058"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC